"Mora C., Maya M.F.","Effect of the rate of temperature increase of the dynamic method on the heat tolerance of fishes",2006,"Journal of Thermal Biology","31","4",,"337","341",,,10.1016/j.jtherbio.2006.01.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33645422270&partnerID=40&md5=93552b781a7bbe0f5a66971896f4a5f3","Leigh Marine Laboratory, University of Auckland, 349 Goat Island Road, Leigh, New Zealand; Seccion de Biología Marina, Universidad del Valle, A.A. 25360, Cali, Colombia","Mora, C., Leigh Marine Laboratory, University of Auckland, 349 Goat Island Road, Leigh, New Zealand; Maya, M.F., Seccion de Biología Marina, Universidad del Valle, A.A. 25360, Cali, Colombia","Heat tolerance is commonly determined by exposing organisms to increasing temperatures until they show symptoms of thermal stress or death. Here we carried out an experiment on a blenny species (Acantemblemaria hancocki; Pisces: Chaenopsidae) and reviewed the literature to evaluate the extent to which variations in the rate at which temperature is increased in experimental trials affects thermal tolerance of fishes. For the blenny species, we found that thermal tolerance decreases significantly from an intermediate heating rate of ∼1°C/h towards quicker and slower heating rates. In the literature we found very few comparisons of thermal tolerance among heating rates (i.e. eight fish species) and although such comparisons were done over narrow ranges of heating rates, overall they appear to follow the pattern described for the blenny species. We discuss a variety of factors including variations in the levels of acclimation, energy use and body quality among heating rates as the causes for this pattern. However, available data are still limited and further research will be necessary to determine the generality and causes of the pattern we found here. Nevertheless, our results indicate the need for caution in the extrapolation of thermal tolerance data when assessing the tolerance of organisms to environmental phenomena that vary in their rates of warming. © 2006 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Critical thermal maximum; Dynamic method; Fishes; Global warming; Heating rates; Thermal tolerance","animal experiment; article; controlled study; fish; heat tolerance; heating; nonhuman; species; temperature; Animalia; Chaenopsidae; Pisces",,,,,,"Addo, A., Chown, S.L., Gaston, K.J., Thermal tolerance, climatic variability and latitude (2000) Proc. Roy. Soc. Lond. B, 267, pp. 739-745; Barker, S.C., Townsend, D.W., Hacunda, J.S., Mortalities of Atlantic hearing, Clupea h. harengus, smooth flounder, Liopsetta putnami, and rainbow smelt, Osmerus mordax, larvae expose to acute thermal shock (1981) Fish. Bull., 79, pp. 198-200; Becker, C.D., Genoway, R.G., Evaluation of the critical thermal maximum for determining thermal tolerance of freshwater fish (1979) Env. Biol. Fish., 4, pp. 245-256; Beitinger, T.L., Bennett, W.A., McCauley, R.W., Temperature tolerance of North American freshwater fishes exposed to dynamic changes in temperature (2000) Environ. Biol. Fish., 58, pp. 237-275; Bennett, W.A., Judd, F.W., Comparison of methods for determining low temperatures tolerance, experimental with Pinfish, Lagodon rhomboides (1992) Copeia, 1992, pp. 1059-1065; Bennett, W., Currier, R.J., Beitinger, T.L., Cold tolerance and potential overwinter of red-bellied piranha, Pygocentrus nattereri, in the United States (1997) Trans. Am. Fish. Soc., 126, pp. 841-849; Chung, K.S., Adaptabilidad de Oreochromis mossambicus (Peters) 1852 a los cambios de temperatura (1985) Acta Científica Venezolana, 36, pp. 180-190; Chung, K.S., Thermal acclimation rate of the tropical long-whiskered catfish Pimelodella chagresi to high temperature (1995) Caribbean J. Sci., 31, pp. 154-156; Chung, K.S., Tolerancia térmica del pez tropical Cyprinodon dearborni (Atheriniformes, Cyprinodontidae) a diversas tasas de calentamiento y salinidades (1997) Rev. Biol. Trop., 45, pp. 1541-1545; Cocking, A.W., The effect of high temperatures on roach (Rutilus rutilus). II: The effect of temperature increasing at a known constant rate (1959) J. Exp. Biol., 36, pp. 217-226; Chung, K.S., Critical thermal maxima and acclimation rate of the tropical guppy Poecilla reticulata (2001) Hydrobiologia, 462, pp. 253-257; Cox, D.K., Effects of three heating rates on the critical thermal maximum of bluegill (1974) Thermal Ecology, pp. 158-163. , J.W. Gibbons R.R. Sharitz US Atomic Energy Commission Savannah, GA; Elliot, J.M., Elliot, J.A., The effect of the rate of temperature increase on the critical thermal maximum for parr of Atlantic salmon and Brown trout (1995) J. Fish Biol., 47, pp. 917-919; Glynn, P.W., D'Croz, L.D., Experimental evidence for high temperatures stress as the cause of El Niño-coincident coral mortality (1990) Coral Reefs, 8, pp. 181-191; Gomez, S.E., Some thermal ecophysiological observations on the catfish Hatcheria macraei (Girard, 1855) (Pisces, Trichomycteridae) (1990) Biota Osorno, 6, pp. 85-89; Hochachka, P.W., Somero, G.N., (1973) Strategies and Biochemical Adaptation, , Saunders Company Publishers Philadelphia; Hutchison, V., Factors influencing thermal tolerance of individual organisms (1976) Symposium Series of the National Technical Information Service, pp. 10-26. , Esch, G.W., McFarlane, R., (Eds.) Springfiled, VA; Hutchison, V., Murphy, K., Behavioral thermoregulation in the salamander Necturus maculosus after heat shock (1985) Comp. Biochem. Physiol. A., 82, pp. 391-394; Kimball, M.E., Miller, J.M., Whitfield, P.E., Hare, J.A., Thermal tolerance and potential distribution of invasive lionfish (Pteroios volitans/miles complex) on the east coast of the United States (2004) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser., 283, pp. 269-278; Kimura, M.T., Cold and heat tolerance of drosophilid flies with reference to their latitudinal distributions (2004) Oecologia, 140, pp. 442-449; Lutterschmidt, W.I., Hutchison, V.H., The critical thermal maximum: History and critique (1997) Can.